Analysis of Washington DC Metro Area Capital Bikeshare 2021¶

by Adeleke Ajibade¶

Introduction¶

Capital Bikeshare (also abbreviated CaBi) is a bicycle-sharing system which serves Washington, D.C.; Arlington County, Virginia; the cities of Alexandria, Virginia and Falls Church, Virginia; Montgomery County, Maryland and Fairfax County, Virginia. As of May 2021, it had 627 stations and 5,400+ bicycles, all owned by these local governments and operated by contractor Motivate International. Opened in September 2010, the system was the largest bike sharing service in the United States until New York City's Citi Bike began operations in May 2013.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 2,749,881 bike rides in Washington DC Metro Area in the year 2021, which was reduced to 2,425,949 after some cleaning was done. There are 12, plus an extra 5 engineered features. The dataset contains features about;

  • ride type : type of bike used (classic, electric or docked)
  • trip duration: how long the trip between end and start time
  • station: start/end name location and geographical location(longitude & latitude)
  • user type: casual(Single Trip, 24-Hour Pass, 3-Day Pass or 5-Day Pass) and member(Annual Member, 30-Day Member or Day Key Member) The dataset was enhanced with features i may find necessary for analysis
  • Rental time: month name, weekday, day, hour, and duration(sec)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in figuring out which period the bike is mostly in use (month, weekday, hour), the user types most preferred bike ride, and which customer users use the bike service the most.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the start time feature will have the most impact on my analysis, customer users, and if the location will affect the bike demand.

"""Computing the relative frequency of the y-axis"""
user_count = df_clean.user_type.value_counts().reindex(['casual','member'])

#getting the total sum
total = user_count.sum()

#maximum proportion of user_type
max_prop = user_count[1]/total

#setting the ytick range and label
tick_prop = np.arange(0,max_prop,0.1)
tick_labels = ['{:.0f}%'.format(i*100) for i in tick_prop]

There is an increasing number of bike trips starting in Spring (March). There was little decrease trend in August as the average temperature during that Summer period tends to be high. The highest number of trips was in October during the Fall, which is the driest season of the year, so users don't have to worry about rain spoiling their trip, unlike in Summer. There was a large decrease during the Winter season as it tends to be cold during that period coupled with snowfall.

# creating a cube root function
def cube_root(x, inverse=False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.cbrt(x)
    else:
        return x**3
    
plt.figure(figsize=[11,6])    
#setting bins range
bins_edge = np.arange(3,148+1,1)
plt.hist(df_clean['duration_sec'].apply(cube_root), bins=bins_edge, color=base_color)
plt.xlim(0,40)
tick = [125, 300,500, 1000, 2000, 3375, 8000, 15625, 27000, 42875, 64000]
plt.xticks(cube_root(np.array(tick)), tick)
plt.xlabel('Seconds')
plt.title('Trip Duration (sec) Distribution',fontsize=15);

The distribution is right skewed with the highest distributions between 500(8 minutes) & 900(15 minutes) seconds ride durations.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration(sec) variable took on a large range of values, and in some cases, some trips lasted for more than 24 hours. so I looked at the data using a Cube Root transform. Under the transformation, the data looked unimodally skewed to the right, with one peak between 500 and 900 seconds.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • There were unusual records in the trip duration(sec). Some durations were having a negative time difference between start time and end time.
  • There were also cases of a trip duration of fewer than 60 seconds with the same start and end station name location. This might be a result of potentially false starts or users trying to re-dock a bike to ensure it's secure.

Above two cases were removed from the dataframe to move forward

Now we see look at what days of the week and time each user type are active

In [59]:
users = ['casual', 'member']
plt.figure(figsize=[18,7])
for i in range(len(users)):
    plt.subplot(1,2,i+1)
    user = df_clean.loc[df_clean['user_type'] == users[i]].groupby(['started_weekday', 'started_hour'])['ride_id'].size().reset_index(name='count')
    user = user.pivot(index='started_hour', columns='started_weekday', values='count')
    ax = sns.heatmap(user, cmap='YlGnBu', cbar_kws={'label':'No. of bike rides'})
    ax.set(xlabel='', ylabel='Hours (24hrs)', title=users[i].capitalize())

The heatmap below depicts users activity and behaviour over the days of the week and time.

Member

  • Users are active during commute hours (7-8 am and 5-7 pm) and every so often during lunch hours of weekdays (Mon - Fri) and are less active on the weekend.
  • There is more activity during the late evening (5-7 pm) of the weekdays and early hours (7-8 am), and this could mean that there is more use of the bike on way back from work compared to in the early morning hours where a user might be running late and decides to take the bus.

Casual

  • Users are more active during the weekend from 9 am to 7 pm and very less active during the weekday. Although occasionally active during the late evening (5 pm - 7 pm) of all days of the week which could mean an evening bike ride stroll.

This proves the claim that most Member users are workers who uses bike ride as a means of commute. The casual users are mostly tourists since they dominated most of the popular start and end stations.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The multivariate exploration showed the distinctive relationship between user's average trip durations on all bike types and usage by users at different times. There was a consistent average trip duration of Member users across the months of the year unlike casual which is double the duration of Members on average. Plotting a heatmap of each user type when bikes are high in demand throughout each hour of the day on each day of the week shed new light on the customer's behavior. Members are most active during the weekdays (Mon - Fri) at commute hours of the day and less active on the weekend. Casual users are most active during the weekends and less active during the late evening of all the days of the week.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The interesting interaction was finding out the activities of each user by days of the week and month unlike the days of the week ride count by users in the bivariate plot. And findings show that they are longer average trip durations between causal than member users.
